Class net.sf.opengroove.client.Contact extends Object implements Serializable

serialVersionUID: -2910467169227988997L

Serialized Fields

userid

String userid
This contact's userid. This must be a userid; it cannot be a username.

realName

String realName
This contact's real name. This is available in the user's user property public-real-name.

localName

String localName
A name set for this contact by the local user. If this is null, then realName should be displayed to the user. If this is not null, then this should be displayed to the user in place of realName.

rsaEncPub

BigInteger rsaEncPub
This field, along with #rsaEncMod, Contact.rsaSigMod, and Contact.rsaSigPub, constitute this contact's public security key. These will be null if hasKeys is false.

rasEncMod

BigInteger rasEncMod

rsaSigPub

BigInteger rsaSigPub

rsaSigMod

BigInteger rsaSigMod

hasKeys

boolean hasKeys
True if the keys for this contact have been obtained, false if not. Messages to be sent to the contact will be queued until the key is available, and the same with received messages.

isUserContact

boolean isUserContact
True if the user is a contact. This may seem somewhat counter-intuitive given the name of this class, but Contact objects are created for all users with which this user corresponds, in order to store the public security keys for those users. This field, then, is true if the user represented by this contact object was added to the contacts list by the local user, and false if this contact object only exists because the local user has corresponded with the user represented by this contact object. For example, a user will be added as a contact object with this field equal to false if that user is a member of a workspace that the local user is also a member of.

When a contact (in the ui sense) is added by the user, they might already have an associated contact object, in which case that object will just have this field set to true. Similarly, when a user deletes a contact, it's contact object is not discarded; this field is simply set to false instead, even if the contact is not a known user by any other means.

isUserVerified

boolean isUserVerified
True if the local user has verified this contact. This means that the local user has reviewed the hash of this contact's security keys and contacted the actual user represented by this contact to validate that those keys are correct, and then indicated to opengroove that they have done this.

computers

ArrayList<E> computers
The list of this contact's computers. This is automatically synchronized every time the local user goes online.

Class net.sf.opengroove.client.LocalUser extends Object implements Serializable

serialVersionUID: 5428195665256519157L

Serialized Fields

userid

String userid
This user's userid. This is used to figure out which server to connect to, as well as to authenticate with that server.

serverRsaPub

BigInteger serverRsaPub
The public security key of this user's realm server.

serverRsaMod

BigInteger serverRsaMod
The security key modulus of this user's realm server.

computer

String computer
The name of this computer that the user has chosen. This is used when authenticating with the server.

rsaEncPub

BigInteger rsaEncPub
This, along with the other rsa fields, contain the user's security keys. These are stored in the public-rsa-enc-pub, public-rsa-enc-mod, public-rsa-sig-pub, and public-rsa-sig-mod user properties. the private keys are not stored on the server.

rsaEncPrv

BigInteger rsaEncPrv

rasEncMod

BigInteger rasEncMod

rsaSigPub

BigInteger rsaSigPub

rsaSigPrv

BigInteger rsaSigPrv

rsaSigMod

BigInteger rsaSigMod

passwordHint

String passwordHint
The user's password hint. The user can set this up in their settings dialog, and it is usually synchronized between computers.

encPassword

String encPassword
The user's encrypted password, in the format returned by Hash.hash(String). This is used to authenticate the user.

autoSignOn

boolean autoSignOn
True if the user should be automatically logged on when OpenGroove starts. storedPassword must not be null if this is true. The hashed value of storedPassword should also match encPassword if this is true.

isSearchVisible

boolean isSearchVisible
True if this user has chosen to be publicly visible. This directly corresponds to CommandCommunicator.getVisibility().

isLocalVisible

boolean isLocalVisible
True if this user has chosen to be locally visible. If this is true, then the user will respond to multicast queries for users on the same network.

realName

String realName
This user's real name. This is made visible in the public-real-name user property.

emailAddress

String emailAddress
This user's private email address. This is the email address that operators of this user's realm server, or OpenGroove administrators themselves, will use to contact this user. This must not be null or the empty string. This is made visible in the email-address user property.

publicEmailAddress

String publicEmailAddress
This user's public email address. This is the email address that others will see as this user's email address. This can be null or the empty string, which usually indicates that this user doesn't want to reveal any email information to other users. This is made visible in the public-email-address user property.

lag

long lag
This user's time lag as compared with the server. This is equal to myTime - serverTime, where myTime is the value of System.currentTimeMillis() invoked on this computer, and serverTime is the value of System.currentTimeMillis() invoked on the server. The server's time can then be reconstructed by evaluating myTime - lag. This allows for time-sensitive operations to be ordered correctly, even if multiple users don't have the same system time on their computers.

This is not synchronized between the user's computers, as it is usually different for all of them.

storedPassword

String storedPassword
If this is not null, then this is the plain-text value of the user's password, and the user won't be prompted for their password when they want to sign on.

cubicBezier

ArrayList<E> cubicBezier
The starting indexes of any sets of 3 points that should define a bezier curve. For example, if there are 6 points, and this array contains one element, namely the number 1, then the second, third, and fourth points will define a bezier curve, while the rest of the points will just define straight lines.
